default8.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOn 
defaultbus, as described above, the bus market outside of London is deregulated and commercial operators are unlikely to choose to run a service that is unprofitable. Where gaps in services emerge, transport authorities must decide whether to fund a 
defaulttendered 
defaultbus 
defaultservice to 
defaultcover unmet transport needs
default.
default Whether they do this will depend on factors such as cost and available budget; the number of people who would use it; whether there are other ways people could
default get around if there was no bus; and likelihood of self-sufficiency in the future.
default8.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCuts to 
defaultpublic spending have left transport authorities less able to fill gaps in this way. Tendered bus services are a non-statutory area of spend making them vulnerable as
default transport authorities seek to ensure they can continue to meet their core legal responsibilities (such as funding free off-peak bus travel for older and disabled people).
default8.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUrban areas have been particularly hard hit
default by public spending cuts
default overall
default. In the 
default2011-12 Local Government Funding Settlement, funding for Metropolitan Districts fell by around 10% in real terms, compared to a 5% cut in Shire areas, relative to the previous year
default. This impacts on transport spending in the cities as PTEs derive nearly th
defaulte entirety of their revenue budget income from a levy on District Councils.
default8.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPTEs are doing all they can to mitigate the effects of these funding challenges, including using the powers and options granted in the Local Transport Act 2008 to protect and impro
defaultve bu
defaults services (see
default section five
default)
default as well as investigating alternative solutions such as walking, cycling, DRT, community transport, car sharing/community car initiatives and taxi services.
default8.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default‘Total Transport’
default approaches
default could also help to ensure that the 
defaultfunding and resources that are available for transport are used as efficiently as possible.
default The public sector provides and funds collective transport in a variety of forms
default,
default 
defaultincluding conventional bus services,
default healthcare services, 
defaultsocial services and educa
defaulttion transport. 
defaultIn addition,
default there is community transport and other voluntary sector collective provision. These services are often provided through different budgets and by different administrative arrangements and can 
defaultsee
default vehicles
default 
defaultunderutilised for large
default parts of the day whilst elsewhere transport needs go unmet. There is scope for greater pooling of budgets and vehicle fleets to provide a single service more cost effectively. 
defaultInvestigation of such an approach was also recommended in the EAC’s transport a
defaultnd the accessibility to public services inquiry
default.
default8.10.
default 
defaultThis 
defaultTotal Transport
default approach is already being applied in some areas of the UK but so far to a very limited effect. Some countries in mainland Europe have gone much further and pooled public transport, educ
defaultation, healthcare and social services budgets into one pot to provide a single transport service – capable of providing a mainstream service which can also flexibly respond to the needs of particular users. 
default8.11.
default 
defaultTotal Transport on a large scale is probably mos
defaultt easily achieved in isolated communities where most public transport is publicly supported, and where the scale of the administration for currently separate budgets and vehicle fleets is more manageable.
default This is not to say that such an approach is straigh
defaulttforward to deliver or that it will be a suitable in all circumstances. However, there are a range of 
defaultexperiences, both from
default 
defaultthe UK
default and abroad that can be drawn upon.
default Following the publication of our report into Total Transport
default, we hosted a practitioner e
defaultvent in 2012 aimed at kick-starting the sharing of lessons 
defaultlearnt
default.
default8.12.
default 
defaultMarketing and behaviour change techniques also have a role to play in making transport for isolated communities more affordable by boosting patronage and thereby making services more financ
defaultially sustainable. Customer engagement and research can help identify passenger needs and motivations and ensure that services provided are the ones people want and will use.
